"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/887215","Home Office","false","2018-04-24","<p>Information on processing of cases against service standards, and on work in progress levels, by case type, is published in the Home Office’s in-country Migration Transparency data, at</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/in-country-migration-data-february-2018" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/in-country-migration-data-february-2018</a></p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2018-04-24T11:55:29.827Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/887215/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/887215/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/887215/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-04-19","Immigration","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how long the average leave to remain application takes from application to decision; and whether there is a backlog.","false","Biography information for Neil Coyle","Bermondsey and Old Southwark","Neil Coyle","136779"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/887216","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-04-24","<p>During 2016-17 and 2017-18 the amount spent on staff salaries within Cefas was £153,000 and £578,000 respectively and in the Marine Management Organisation was £57,000 and £307,000 respectively in line with the support and advisory roles they provide. Within UK Overseas Territory Governments, salaries were £50,259 in 2016-17 and £109,148.81 in 2017-18.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2018-04-24T16:02:26.783Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/887216/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/887216/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/887216/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-04-19","British Overseas Territories: Marine Protected Areas","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, how much of the funding for the UK Overseas Territories Blue Belt programme was spent on staff salaries in (a) the Centre for Environment, Fisheries and Aquaculture Science, (b) the Marine Management Organisation and (c) UK Overseas Territory governments in (i) 2016-17 and (ii) 2017-18.","false","Biography information for Zac Goldsmith","Richmond Park","Zac Goldsmith","136780"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/887217","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-04-24","<p>​The Overseas Territory Governments which received direct funding from the Blue Belt Programme were the Ascension Island Government (£300,000 in both 2016-17 and 2017-18), British Indian Ocean Territory Administration (£725,000 in 2017-18 to part fund a maritime patrol vessel), St Helena Government (£39,500 in 2017-18), Tristan Da Cunha Government (£140,000 in 2017-18) and the Government of South Georgia and South Sandwich Islands (£52,500 in 2017-18). In both periods, up to £500,000 per year was available to all Territories through the Overseas Territories Environment and Climate Fund (also known as Darwin Plus) for bespoke marine projects.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2018-04-24T16:04:16.02Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/887217/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/887217/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/887217/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-04-19","British Overseas Territories: Marine Protected Areas","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, how much funding from the UK Overseas Territories Blue Belt programme was transferred directly to each of the Overseas Territory governments to spend on their local marine conservation priorities in (i) 2016-17 and (ii) 2017-18.","false","Biography information for Zac Goldsmith","Richmond Park","Zac Goldsmith","136781"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/887218","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-04-24","<p>All scientific surveys undertaken through the Blue Belt programme are designed in line with international best practice. There were no incidental mortalities of turtle or seabird species as a result of the scientific surveys undertaken through the Blue Belt programme in either 2016-17 or 2017-18. Where possible all sharks are released alive during surveys, but in 2017-18 seven sharks (Notorynchus cepedianus) were killed through depredation by other species during surveys in Tristan da Cunha.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2018-04-24T16:10:59.763Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/887218/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/887218/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/887218/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-04-19","British Overseas Territories: Marine Protected Areas","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what information his Department holds on how many (a) turtles, (b) sharks and (c) seabirds were killed as a result of activities funded by the UK Overseas Territories Blue Belt programme in (i) 2016-17 and (ii) 2017-18.","false","Biography information for Zac Goldsmith","Richmond Park","Zac Goldsmith","136782"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/887219","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-04-24","<p>All scientific surveys undertaken through the Blue Belt programme are designed in line with international best practice, and undertake consideration of all potential impacts together with mitigation measures to limit such impacts, pre-deployment. There was no by-catch in 2016-17. During the 2017-18 fish stock assessment and tagging research, undertaken at the request of the Government of Tristan Da Cunha, specific gear was employed which limited the incidental mortality of non-target species but seven sharks (Notorynchus cepedianus) were killed through depredation by other species.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2018-04-24T16:14:51.7Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/887219/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/887219/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/887219/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-04-19","British Overseas Territories: Marine Protected Areas","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what proportion of by-catch was caught by activities funded by the UK Overseas Territories Blue Belt programme in each of the participating Overseas Territories in (i) 2016-17 and (ii) 2017-18.","false","Biography information for Zac Goldsmith","Richmond Park","Zac Goldsmith","136783"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/887220","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-04-24","<p>The Government currently has no plans to review the level of business rates relief for childcare providers.</p><p>The Government has introduced a package of support on business rates worth over £10 billion by 2023. This includes permanently doubling Small Business Rate Relief to 100 per cent, taking over 600,000 small businesses out of paying business rates entirely, and a £435 million package of support for ratepayers facing the steepest increases in bills following the 2017 revaluation. Furthermore, all business, including childcare providers, will benefit from the Government’s decision to bring forward the switch of the annual indexation of business rates from RPI to CPI by two years to April 2018. This measure alone will be worth £2.3 billion over 5 years.</p>","Richmond (Yorks)","Rishi Sunak",,"2018-04-24T16:40:33.827Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/887220/answer","Biography information for Rishi Sunak","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/887220/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/887220/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-04-19","Non-domestic Rates","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, whether he plans to review the level of business rate relief for childcare providers.","false","Biography information for Tracy Brabin","Batley and Spen","Tracy Brabin","136784"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/887221","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-04-24","<p>All scientific surveys undertaken through the Blue Belt programme are designed in line with international best practice, particularly in terms of seabird mortality mitigation measures. No International Union for Conservation of Nature red-listed species were killed or injured when undertaking scientific surveys during 2016-17 or 2017-18.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2018-04-24T16:09:02.643Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/887221/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/887221/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/887221/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-04-19","British Overseas Territories: Marine Protected Areas","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, how many International Union for Conservation of Nature red-listed species were killed as a result of activities funded by the UK Overseas Territories Blue Belt programme in each of the participating Overseas Territories in (i) 2016-17 and (ii) 2017-18.","false","Biography information for Zac Goldsmith","Richmond Park","Zac Goldsmith","136785"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/887222","Treasury","false","2018-04-24","<p>As of 19 April 2018, more than 275,000 parents had opened a Tax–Free Childcare account and over 60,000 parents had used their account to make a payment to a childcare provider.</p>","South West Norfolk","Elizabeth Truss",,"2018-04-24T12:46:46.54Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/887222/answer","Biography information for Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/887222/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/887222/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2018-04-19","Children: Day Care","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many tax-free childcare accounts have (a) been created and (b) had at least one payment made from that account to date.","false","Biography information for Tracy Brabin","Batley and Spen","Tracy Brabin","136786"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/887223","Department for Education","false","2018-04-24","<p>The department is working with local authorities, fostering service providers, foster carers and others in the sector to develop plans to allow foster carers to access the additional 30 hours free childcare for their foster children where it is right for the child.</p><p> </p><p>We plan to implement this change in time for September 2018. More detail will be set out shortly.</p><p> </p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi",,"2018-04-24T16:15:07.413Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/887223/answer","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/887223/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/887223/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-04-19","Children: Day Care","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, when he plans to provide more information on the roll-out of 30 hours free childcare for fostered children.","false","Biography information for Tracy Brabin","Batley and Spen","Tracy Brabin","136787"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/887224","Department for Education","false","2018-04-24","<p>793 Nursing, Midwifery and Allied Health Professions students are currently known to have received an overpayment of student support because of an error by the Student Loans Company (SLC).</p><p> </p><p>The government announced on 18 April 2018 that the SLC will provide support to ensure that none of the students affected by the error suffer hardship.</p><p> </p><p>Students affected by this error will be eligible to apply for additional, non-repayable, support of up to £1,000 for the remainder of this academic year, and should contact SLC. In addition, repayment of overpaid maintenance support will be deferred for all students affected until they have finished their courses and can afford to repay.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2018-04-24T15:51:27.047Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/887224/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/887224/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/887224/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-04-19","Students: Loans","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what estimate he has made of the number students in receipt of an NHS Bursary who have been incorrectly awarded a maintenance loan; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","136788"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/887225","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-04-27","<p>No assessment has been made of recent trends in waiting times to access children’s speech and language therapy services as this data is not reported centrally. There are no mandated referral to treatment times for speech and language therapy services. Local commissioners have responsibility for assessing the needs of their local population, and arranging services to meet those needs.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2018-04-27T10:43:14.243Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/887225/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/887225/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/887225/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-04-19","Speech and Language Therapy: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what assessment he has made of recent trends in waiting times to access children’s speech and language therapy services.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","136789"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/887226","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-04-27","<p>The Department of Health and Social Care are working with the Department for Education and Public Health England to enable early years professionals to identify and support children’s early speech, language and communication needs. In an exchange of letters with the former Minister of State for Children and Families (Robert Goodwill MP) last November, the Department agreed to ensure that we and Public Health England prioritise the required activities to support the social mobility action plan launched in December 2017. Detailed work is ongoing between the Department for Education and Public Health England.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2018-04-27T10:54:22.75Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/887226/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/887226/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/887226/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-04-19","Speech and Language Therapy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what recent discussions he has had with the Secretary of State for Education on the role of speech and language therapy services in developing communication and literacy skills.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","136790"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/887227","Department for Education","false","2018-04-24","<p>The average Attainment 8 score of pupils, at the end of key stage 4<a href="https://educationgovuk.sharepoint.com/sites/cd/c/WorkplaceDocuments/Written%20PQ%20Team/Written%20PQ%20-%202017-18%20drafts/136791%20QC%20200418.docx#_ftn1" target="_blank">[1]</a> in state-funded schools<a href="https://educationgovuk.sharepoint.com/sites/cd/c/WorkplaceDocuments/Written%20PQ%20Team/Written%20PQ%20-%202017-18%20drafts/136791%20QC%20200418.docx#_ftn2" target="_blank">[2]</a>, split by eligibility for free school meals (FSM)<a href="https://educationgovuk.sharepoint.com/sites/cd/c/WorkplaceDocuments/Written%20PQ%20Team/Written%20PQ%20-%202017-18%20drafts/136791%20QC%20200418.docx#_ftn3" target="_blank">[3]</a> in each requested parliamentary constituency<a href="https://educationgovuk.sharepoint.com/sites/cd/c/WorkplaceDocuments/Written%20PQ%20Team/Written%20PQ%20-%202017-18%20drafts/136791%20QC%20200418.docx#_ftn4" target="_blank">[4]</a> for 2016/17<a href="https://educationgovuk.sharepoint.com/sites/cd/c/WorkplaceDocuments/Written%20PQ%20Team/Written%20PQ%20-%202017-18%20drafts/136791%20QC%20200418.docx#_ftn5" target="_blank">[5]</a> is in the attached table.</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://educationgovuk.sharepoint.com/sites/cd/c/WorkplaceDocuments/Written%20PQ%20Team/Written%20PQ%20-%202017-18%20drafts/136791%20QC%20200418.docx#_ftnref1" target="_blank">[1]</a> Pupils are identified as being at the end of key stage 4 if they were on roll at the school and in Year 11 at the time of the January school census for that year. Age is calculated as at 31 August for that year, and the majority of pupils at the end of key stage 4 were age 15 at the start of the academic year. Some pupils may complete this key stage in an earlier or later year group.</p><p><a href="https://educationgovuk.sharepoint.com/sites/cd/c/WorkplaceDocuments/Written%20PQ%20Team/Written%20PQ%20-%202017-18%20drafts/136791%20QC%20200418.docx#_ftnref2" target="_blank">[2]</a> State-funded schools include academies, free schools, city technology colleges, further education colleges with provision for 14- to 16-year-olds and state-funded special schools. They exclude independent schools, independent special schools, non-maintained special schools, hospital schools and alternative provision.</p><p><a href="https://educationgovuk.sharepoint.com/sites/cd/c/WorkplaceDocuments/Written%20PQ%20Team/Written%20PQ%20-%202017-18%20drafts/136791%20QC%20200418.docx#_ftnref3" target="_blank">[3]</a> Eligibility for FSM is taken from the school census for that year. Pupils whose FSM status is unknown are included as ‘all other pupils’.</p><p><a href="https://educationgovuk.sharepoint.com/sites/cd/c/WorkplaceDocuments/Written%20PQ%20Team/Written%20PQ%20-%202017-18%20drafts/136791%20QC%20200418.docx#_ftnref4" target="_blank">[4]</a> Figures are based on the parliamentary constituency of the pupil’s postcode and not the school’s postcode, therefore they will not match the published data from the ‘pupil residency and school location tables’ located here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/revised-gcse-and-equivalent-results-in-england-2015-to-2016" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/revised-gcse-and-equivalent-results-in-england-2015-to-2016</a>.</p><p><a href="https://educationgovuk.sharepoint.com/sites/cd/c/WorkplaceDocuments/Written%20PQ%20Team/Written%20PQ%20-%202017-18%20drafts/136791%20QC%20200418.docx#_ftnref5" target="_blank">[5]</a> Figures are based on revised data.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2018-04-24T16:57:18.757Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/887227/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/887227/answer","Attainment_8_score_of_ pupils.doc","Attainment_8_score_of_ pupils.doc","Average_attainment_8_score_at_the_end_of_KS4","Average_attainment_8_score_at_the_end_of_KS4","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/887227/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-04-19","Pupils: Nottinghamshire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what the average Attainment 8 score was per pupil who was (a) eligible and (b) not eligible for free school meals in (i) Ashfield, (ii) Mansfield and (iii) Rushcliffe in 2017.","false","Biography information for Gloria De Piero","Ashfield","Gloria De Piero","136791"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/887228","Department for Transport","false","2018-04-25","<p>Our ambition is to ensure that passengers across the rail network can use mobile phones, bar codes and smart cards across almost all of the network by the end of this year. This will mean every passenger will have the choice of travelling without a paper ticket and we do not currently have any plans to withdraw paper tickets.</p><p> </p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2018-04-25T14:04:54.887Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/887228/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/887228/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/887228/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-04-19","Railways: Tickets","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what steps is he taking to ensure that the roll-out of smart ticketing on the rail network does not exclude people without access to the necessary technology from purchasing rail travel.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","136792"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/887229","Treasury","false","2018-04-24","<p>HMRC publishes statistics on the estimated costs of minor tax reliefs available on Gov.uk. Where the cost of reliefs are estimated to be negligible (‘neg’), the cost is believed to be less than £3m per year. Precise estimates are not available for some of these reliefs and therefore a total figure across negligible reliefs is not held.</p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride",,"2018-04-24T16:33:56.353Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/887229/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/887229/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/887229/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2018-04-19","Tax Allowances","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, pursuant to the Answer of 13 April 2018 to Question 135470, what the total figure is for all of the minor tax reliefs that his Department considers to be negligible.","false","Biography information for Peter Dowd","Bootle","Peter Dowd","136793"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/887230","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-04-26","<p>Prior to the decision to uplift patient charges, the Department undertook an equality analysis and impact assessment. These have been published and can be found at the following link:</p><p> </p><p><a href="http://www.legislation.gov.uk/uksi/2018/336/resources" target="_blank">http://www.legislation.gov.uk/uksi/2018/336/resources</a></p><p> </p><p>The current exemption and charge remission arrangements are intended to ensure that individuals are not deterred from obtaining any necessary treatment on financial grounds.</p><p> </p><p>There has been no change to the exemption arrangements as a result of current increases to National Health Service dental charges. NHS dental treatment remains free for those under the age of 18, those under the age of 19 and in full-time education, pregnant women, those who have had a baby in the previous 12 months and those on low incomes.</p><p> </p><p>In addition, adults who are not in receipt of qualifying benefits, but are on a low income, may qualify for full or partial help with charges through the NHS Low Income Scheme.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2018-04-26T10:19:38.017Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/887230/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/887230/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/887230/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-04-19","Dental Services: Fees and Charges","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what assessment he has made of the potential effect of the increase in NHS dental charges from 1 April 2018 on people’s (a) ability to pay for such services and (b) decision to access such services.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","136794"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/887231","Department for Education","false","2018-04-24","<p>The attached tables provide the number of apprenticeship starts in each of the last four academic year quarters for a) Nottingham unitary authority and b) the East Midlands region broken down by each level.</p><p> </p><p>For additional geographical and level breakdowns please see the Apprenticeships Geography tools in the Further Education data library:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/fe-data-library-apprenticeships" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/fe-data-library-apprenticeships</a>.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2018-04-24T16:44:28.02Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/887231/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/887231/answer","136795 Apprenticeship starts for Nottingham unitary authority and East Midlands region.pdf","136795 Apprenticeship starts for Nottingham unitary authority and East Midlands region.pdf","Apprenticecship_starts_Nottingham_East_Midlands","Apprenticecship_starts_Nottingham_East_Midlands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/887231/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-04-19","Apprentices: East Midlands","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many apprenticeship starts there have been in (a) Nottinghamshire and (b) the East Midlands at every level offered in each of the last four quarters.","false","Biography information for Gloria De Piero","Ashfield","Gloria De Piero","136795"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/887232","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-04-26","<p>We have passed new legislation which replaces the existing law on the sale of pets. Under The Animal Welfare (Licensing of Activities Involving Animals) (England) Regulations 2018 it is clear that anyone in the business of selling pets, whether online or from a traditional pet shop, will need a licence from their local authority. The new regulations come into force on 1 October and will be enforced by local authorities.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2018-04-26T17:12:22.537Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/887232/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/887232/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/887232/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-04-19","Pets: Sales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what assessment he has made of the effectiveness of existing legislation regulating the online sale of pets.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","136796"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/887233","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-05-09","<p>This information is not held centrally and can only be obtained at disproportionate cost. Records of prosecutions for offences under section 1 of the Theft Act 1968 do not provide breakdowns of the item or animal stolen.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2018-05-09T13:42:42.497Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/887233/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/887233/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/887233/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-04-19","Pets: Theft","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, how many people have been prosecuted for pet theft in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","136797"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/887234","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-04-24","<p>Currently, when one member of a couple has reached Pension Credit qualifying age, that member may claim Pension Credit for the couple. Under the Welfare Reform Act 2012, in order to ensure that the younger partner is subject to the same labour-market conditions as other people of the same age, couples needing benefit support where one member of the couple has yet to reach Pension Credit qualifying age will need to claim Universal Credit rather than Pension Credit. This will apply to new claims only. Existing claims to Pension Credit from such couples will be protected.</p><p>A number of Impact Assessments were published to support the passage of the Welfare Reform Act 2012 through Parliament; including the Universal Credit Impact Assessment on 10 December 2012. This can be found on GOV.UK at: <a href="https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/220177/universal-credit-wr2011-ia.pdf" target="_blank">https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/220177/universal-credit-wr2011-ia.pdf</a></p>","Hexham","Guy Opperman",,"2018-04-24T15:11:20.797Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/887234/answer","Biography information for Guy Opperman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/887234/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/887234/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-04-19","Pension Credit and Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what assessment she has made of the effect of universal credit and pension credit regulations on couples where one person is over the pension age and the other is below that age.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","136798"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/887235","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-04-24","<p>In 2018 the Department provided £4 million of Official Development Assistance funding to the World Health Emergencies Programme Contingency Fund which was set up in 2015 following the Ebola outbreak. The World Health Organization is responsible for the allocation of funds provided to the World Health Emergencies Programme Contingency Fund.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2018-04-24T15:34:37.293Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/887235/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/887235/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/887235/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-04-19","Ebola","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, how much funding was allocated to the Ebola contingency fund; and how much of that funding has been reallocated to other programmes.","false","Biography information for Imran Hussain","Bradford East","Imran Hussain","136799"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/887236","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-04-24","<p>I have replied to the hon. Members.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2018-04-24T16:09:32.227Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/887236/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/887236/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/887236/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-04-19","Members: Correspondence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, when the Minister of State for Energy and Clean Growth plans to respond to the letter from the hon. Members for Ashfield and Blaenau Gwent of 5 March 2018 on the Mineworkers Pension Scheme.","false","Biography information for Gloria De Piero","Ashfield","Gloria De Piero","136800"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/887237","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-04-25","<p>The Central Equine Database (CED) was launched on 8 March 2018. Legislation to implement current EU law on equine identification, including the CED, is being prepared and will be laid before Parliament as soon as practicable.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2018-04-25T11:56:40.567Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/887237/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/887237/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/887237/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-04-19","Horses: Databases","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, whether he plans bring forward legislative proposals on statutory equine identification for a central equine database.","false","Biography information for Sir Mark Hendrick","Preston","Sir Mark Hendrick","136801"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/887238","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-04-24","<p>Officials from the Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government have discussed with the Department for Transport the provision of Changing Places toilets. Both departments have met to talk with representatives of the Changing Places consortium to review current and forecast provision in National Rail stations.</p>","South Derbyshire","Mrs Heather Wheeler",,"2018-04-24T16:32:45.72Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/887238/answer","Biography information for Mrs Heather Wheeler","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/887238/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/887238/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-04-19","Public Lavatories: Railway Stations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, what discussions his Department has had with the Department for Transport on the number of changing places toilet facilities at National Rail stations.","false","Biography information for Layla Moran","Oxford West and Abingdon","Layla Moran","136802"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/887239","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-04-26","<p>We received the mentioned letter on 7 February 2018 and a reply was sent on the 17 April 2018. We have forwarded an additional copy to your office for your records.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2018-04-26T16:26:05.703Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/887239/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/887239/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/887239/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-04-19","Members: Correspondence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, when the Parliamentary Under Secretary of State for the Environment plans to respond to the letter of 29 January 2018 from the hon. Member for Newcastle upon Tyne North on the Food Insecurity Bill.","false","Biography information for Catherine McKinnell","Newcastle upon Tyne North","Catherine McKinnell","136803"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/887240","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-04-24","<p>A response was sent to the letter dated 7 December 2017 on 8 January 2018. Despite a comprehensive search of Departmental records we are unable to locate any letter of 9 March 2018. A replacement letter will be sent today, providing a further explanation and include a copy of the letter dated 8 January 2018.</p>","Hexham","Guy Opperman",,"2018-04-24T13:30:19.463Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/887240/answer","Biography information for Guy Opperman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/887240/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/887240/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-04-19","Members: Correspondence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, when she plans to respond to the letters of 7 December 2017 and 9 March 2018 from the hon. Member for Newcastle upon Tyne North on the stage 3 complaint from a constituent about changes to the state pension age.","false","Biography information for Catherine McKinnell","Newcastle upon Tyne North","Catherine McKinnell","136804"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/887241","Home Office","false","2018-04-24","<p>The Home Office does not hold the information requested.</p><p> </p><p>The Home Office collects and publishes data for offences involving knives or sharp instruments for selected offences in England and Wales, at police force area level only.</p><p> </p><p>These data are published quarterly, available here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/675512/prc-knife-open-data-march2009-onwards-tables.ods" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/675512/prc-knife-open-data-march2009-onwards-tables.ods</a></p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2018-04-24T12:12:52.587Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/887241/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/887241/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/887241/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-04-19","Knives: Crime","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what estimate he has made of the number of knife crime incidents in Newcastle in each of the last seven years.","false","Biography information for Catherine McKinnell","Newcastle upon Tyne North","Catherine McKinnell","136805"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/887242","Treasury","false","2018-04-24","<p>The Financial Conduct Authority (FCA) is an independent non-governmental body responsible for regulating and supervising the financial services industry, and is funded entirely via a levy on the firms it regulates.</p><p> </p><p>The government has given the FCA three operational objectives: to ensure an appropriate degree of protection for consumers; protect and enhance the integrity of the UK financial system; and to promote effective competition in the interests of consumers.</p><p> </p><p>As an independent body, it is for the FCA to decide how to fund and allocate its resources most effectively to meet these statutory objectives. The government will continue to work with the FCA to ensure that financial services are regulated effectively after the UK leaves the EU.</p>","Salisbury","John Glen",,"2018-04-24T13:55:33.52Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/887242/answer","Biography information for John Glen","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/887242/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/887242/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2018-04-19","Financial Services","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, with reference to the Financial Times article of 9 April 2018, FCA to scale back non-Brexit activities, what steps his Department is taking to ensure that financial services are regulated during the transition period after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Catherine McKinnell","Newcastle upon Tyne North","Catherine McKinnell","136806"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/887243","Department for Transport","false","2018-04-24","<p>The Task and Finish group on Taxi and Private Hire Vehicles has meet on nine occasions. The group is independent so I have not attended any group meetings.</p><p> </p><p>The group is expected to submit its report shortly.</p>","Wealden","Ms Nusrat Ghani",,"2018-04-24T15:21:07.443Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/887243/answer","Biography information for Ms Nusrat Ghani","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/887243/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/887243/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-04-19","Taxis","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answer of 26 February 2018 to Question 127728, on licensing of cross-border taxi’s and private hire vehicles, how many times the Task and Finish group has met; whether the Minister has met the group; and when the group will report its findings.","false","Biography information for Matt Rodda","Reading East","Matt Rodda","136807"
